  "local_port": 51372,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What IDE do you use for C/C++?",
  "response": "There are several popular Integrated Development Environments (IDEs) for C and C++ development, each with its own set of features and capabilities. Here are some of the most commonly used ones:\n\n1. **Visual Studio (Visual Studio Community/Professional/Enterprise)**:\n   - **Platform**: Windows (with limited support for macOS and Linux via Visual Studio Code and remote development).\n   - **Features**: Robust debugging, IntelliSense, Git integration, extensive plugin support, and performance profiling.\n   - **Use Case**: Ideal for large-scale projects and professional development.\n\n2. **Visual Studio Code (VS Code)**:\n   - **Platform**: Windows, macOS, Linux.\n   - **Features**: Lightweight, highly customizable with extensions, excellent C/C++ support via the C/C++ Extension by Microsoft.\n   - **Use Case**: Suitable for developers who prefer a text editor with IDE-like features.\n\n3. **CLion**:\n   - **Platform**: Windows, macOS, Linux.\n   - **Features**: Intelligent code assistance, integrated debugger, CMake support, and version control integration.\n   - **Use Case**: Great for C++ developers who need a powerful and modern IDE.\n\n4. **Eclipse (with CDT - C/C++ Development Tooling)**:\n   - **Platform**: Windows, macOS, Linux.\n   - **Features**: Open-source, extensible via plugins, good for large projects with complex build systems.\n   - **Use Case**: Suitable for developers who prefer open-source tools and need extensive plugin support.\n\n5. **Code::Blocks**:\n   - **Platform**: Windows, macOS, Linux.\n   - **Features**: Open-source, supports multiple compilers, simple and straightforward interface.\n   - **Use Case**: Ideal for beginners and small to medium-sized projects.\n\n6. **QtCreator**:\n   - **Platform**: Windows, macOS, Linux.\n   - **Features**: Integrated with the Qt framework, excellent for GUI development, supports CMake and QMake.\n   - **Use Case**: Perfect for Qt-based applications and cross-platform development.\n\n7. **Xcode**:\n   - **Platform**: macOS.\n   - **Features**: Designed for macOS and iOS development, integrates well with Apple's development ecosystem, includes a powerful debugger and interface builder.\n   - **Use Case**: Best for macOS and iOS developers.\n\nChoosing the right IDE depends on your specific needs, such as the platform you're developing on, the complexity of your projects, and your personal preferences in terms of workflow and features.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
